05100nam a2200661Ia 9780801454738DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979630432  a97808014547387 a10.7591/97808014547382doi  a(DE-B1597)480040  a(OCoLC)905564277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE744b.J665 2016 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a327.73009042231 aJohnstone, Andrew E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAgainst Immediate Evil :bAmerican Internationalists and the Four Freedoms on the Eve of World War II /cAndrew E. Johnstone. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Four Freedoms -- t1. The Sino-Japanese War and the American Committee for Non-Participation in Japanese Aggression -- t2. The Coming of War and the American Union for Concerted Peace Efforts -- t3. The Phony War and the Non-Partisan Committee for Peace through Revision of the Neutrality Law -- t4. Blitzkrieg and the Committee to Defend America by Aiding the Allies -- t5. The Destroyer-Bases Agreement and the Century Group -- t6. Maximum Aid and the Battle for Lend-Lease -- t7. Deliver the Goods and Fight for Freedom -- t8. The Battle of the Atlantic from Barbarossa to Pearl Harbor -- tEpilogue: War and Beyond -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Against Immediate Evil, Andrew Johnstone tells the story of how internationalist Americans worked between 1938 and 1941 to convince the U.S. government and the American public of the need to stem the rising global tide of fascist aggression. As war approached, the internationalist movement attempted to arouse the nation in order to defeat noninterventionism at home and fascism overseas. Johnstone's examination of this movement undermines the common belief that the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor wrenched an isolationist United States into global armed conflict and the struggle for international power.Johnstone focuses on three organizations—the American Committee for Non-Participation in Japanese Aggression, the Committee to Defend America by Aiding the Allies, and Fight For Freedom—that actively promoted a more global role for the United States based on a conception of the "four freedoms" later made famous by FDR. The desire to be free from fear was seen in concerns regarding America’s immediate national security. The desire to be free from want was expressed in anxieties over the nation’s future economic prosperity. The need for freedom of speech was represented in concerns over the potential loss of political freedoms. Finally, the need for freedom of worship was seen in the emphasis on religious freedoms and broader fears about the future of Western civilization. These groups and their supporters among the public and within the government characterized the growing global conflict as one between two distinct worlds and in doing so, set the tone of American foreign policy for decades to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternationalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeutralityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic opinionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aUnited States, internationalist Americans, internationalist movement, fascist aggression, World War II, noninterventionism, international power, global conflict, national security, foreign policy, world affairs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-